aws::graph::propositions: # Helicopter Hydraulic System Procedures and Safety Information
[CWP] requires checking if HYDR light flashes.
Yaw servo hydraulic switch is located on collective grip.
Yaw servo hydraulic switch should be set to ON during preflight checks.
When yaw servo hydraulic switch is ON, no forces should be felt on yaw pedals.
No forces on yaw pedals indicates the system is boosted.
[HYD TEST] or [ACCU TST] should be RESET in the up position.
CWP should be checked when [HYD TEST] or [ACCU TST] is RESET.
HYDR light illuminates when [HYD TEST] or [ACCU TST] is RESET.
The helicopter manufacturer issued a warning about hydraulic system checks.
If a pilot fails to restore the yaw servo hydraulic switch to "on" prior to takeoff, there will be a lack of hydraulic boost to the tail rotor system.
The yaw servo hydraulic switch "on" position is the forward position.
The yaw load compensator is discharged earlier in the preflight checklist.
The yaw load compensator is discharged to verify proper operation of the HYD/ACCU Test switch and valve.
Airbus Helicopters issued Safety Information Notice 2776-S-29 on August 21, 2014.
Safety Information Notice 2776-S-29 reminds pilots of procedural differences between dual hydraulic systems and single hydraulic systems.
Safety Information Notice 2776-S-29 warns pilots about consequences if the yaw servo hydraulic switch is not restored to the "on" position during the Hydraulic Pressure Isolation Check.
Safety Information Notice 2776-S-29 informed pilots of improvements to the dual hydraulic circuit.

text:
c. [CWP]: Check HYDR light flashes.
   d. Yaw servo hydraulic switch on collective grip; ON. Check no forces are felt on yaw pedals (boosted).
   e. [HYD TEST] or [ACCU TST]  RESET in the up position. CWP  Check. HYDR light illuminates.

According to the helicopter manufacturer, if during the hydraulic system check, the pilot fails to restore the yaw servo hydraulic switch to "on" (forward position) prior to takeoff, there will be a lack of hydraulic boost to the tail rotor system, because earlier in the preflight checklist, the yaw load compensator will have been discharged to verify proper operation of the HYD/ACCU (Hydraulic Accumulator) Test switch and valve.

On August 21, 2014, Airbus Helicopters issued Safety Information Notice 2776-S-29 to remind pilots of the procedural differences that exist for the run-up hydraulic checks for the dual hydraulic system as compared to the single hydraulic systems, and to warn pilots of what can happen if the yaw servo hydraulic switch is not restored to the 'on" position during the Hydraulic Pressure Isolation Check.
